
I am enclosing gzipped, tarred files containing MSTK and MSTKutil sources 
version N.n. The following steps describe how to make, install and use
the MSTK and MSTutil libraries. In the descriptions, substitute N.n by
the major and minor version numbers of MSTK that you downloaded (for
example, 1.5).


------------------------------------------------------------------------
A.      --------- Make and install MSTK Utilities ----------------
------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. Unpack the sources by issuing the commands
     tar xvzf MSTK-N.n.tar.gz   - creates directories mstkutil-N.n and mstk-N.n

2. cd to mstkutil-N.n

3. Type './setup' which will setup subdirs for compilation on i686
   machines running linux. For a different architecture, type ./setup
   archos, where archos is the architecture and OS code for the
   system, e.g., ibm_aix9, hp_ux10 etc.

4. Edit the Makefile to reflect the architecture and os specified to
   setup. Edit the compiler and compiler flags (ONLY IF NECESSARY). In
   general, on a Linux system you have to make little or no change to
   the Makefile. 

5. Also edit the TOPDIR variable in the Makefile to reflect where the
   mstk and mstkutil directories are located. For example, if both
   mstkutil and mstk directories are in the directory $HOME/develop/,
   then set TOPDIR to $HOME/develop.

5. Type 'make' to make the debug and optimized versions of the
   libraries which are ./lib/$ARCHOS/libmstkutil-d.a and
   ./lib/$ARCHOS/libmstkutil.a respectively.

6. Edit the 'install' file and modify the INSTALL_TOPDIR variable to
   be where you want the header files and include files to be
   installed. It could be $HOME or /usr/local. 

   Then type 'install N.n' (e.g., 'install 1.5')

   The script will install the header files in
   $INSTALL_TOPDIR/include/mstkutil-N.n. If you answer 'y' to the
   question "Do you to make the installed version the default?", it
   will make a symbolic link to it called
   $INSTALL_TOPDIR/include/mstkutil


------------------------------------------------------------------------
B.      --------- Make and install MSTK ----------------
------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. Repeat step 1 to 7 in section A for MSTK starting with unzipping
   and untarring mstk.tar.gz


*************************
NOTE:NOTE:NOTE:
*************************

	To include the mesh partitioning code MESH_Partition with
	METIS, you have to type 'make PAR=1'

*************************


------------------------------------------------------------------------
B.      --------- Use MSTK for code development ----------------
------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. Read the manual !!!!! It is in .../mstk-N.n/docs/

2. Include "MSTK.h" in any code that uses MSTK

3. Edit the makefile to indicate the paths to MSTK Util and MSTK
   libraries. If necessary, also indicate where the metis library
   paths are.

4. Include "-lmstk -lmstkutil" on the link line.




NOTES:
-------------------------------------------------------------------------

The make file arguments have changed in this version of MSTK. Now just
typing 'make' will make the debug and optimized versions - No need to
type 'make' and 'make opt' separately. 'make PAR=1' will include the
mesh partitioning routines and you must link with METIS

I have tested MSTK only on a Linux system with the gcc compiler. I do not 
see why it should not work on other systems with a ANSI compliant 
compiler. If it doesn't, please let me know. On other machines tar may
not support the -z option. In this case, gunzip the file first and
then issue a 'tar xvf file.tar' command.

Feel free to contact me if you need any assistance. Also, see the MSTK
website http://math.lanl.gov/~rao/Meshing-Projects/MSTK/

Regards
Rao


